Police have deployed an armoured vehicle to pry open the cabin of a lorry on a motorway in Texas.

The driver refused to stop, or get out of the cab when officers used spike strips to stop the vehicle, police said.

After the armoured vehicle tore open a window, police threw in a gas canister, before going inside and pulling the driver out.

It is unclear what started the chase, but police said the driver used "evasive manoeuvres", changing lanes multiple times and swerving.

“We still don’t know why he was acting in the erratic manner that he was,” Harris County Sheriff Ed Gonzalez told journalists, adding that he appeared to have "some heavy impairment".

Authorities were able to track the vehicle, using aerial assistance and ground units, but the driver continued to evade capture.

Surveillance footage showed the driver exiting the vehicle and making a run for the store, where he disappeared from view.

The investigating officer's eyes scanned the footage, frozen on the image of the fleeing suspect as he ducked into the brightly lit convenience store. The door's swing and the sound of clinking glass bottles hinted at a chaotic pursuit on the other side, yet the surveillance cameras had been unable to capture another glimpse of the culprit once he disappeared into the store's crowded interior.

Inside, the officer, a seasoned veteran of the department, was determined to make sense of the grainy black and white footage, his eyes scanning the paused image of a figure in a faded blue jacket, the store's surveillance camera having captured the person's frantic struggle for a moment or two before fading into nothingness, a moment's chaos that left as many questions as answers.

The detective's mind was awhirl with theories and scenarios, but something didn't seem right, and he couldn't shake the feeling that this footage, despite its fleeting glimpse of activity, was hiding more than it revealed, that there was a story lurking beneath the static darkness of the store's camera, waiting to be uncovered.
